</hint>

<p>Let's compare the values of the actual function <m>f(x)</m> and this particular linear approximation <m>L_{ $x1  }(x)</m> for the following values: <m>x=1, 2, 1.9, 2.1, 10</m>.   (For all these values of <m>x</m>, we are still using the linear approximation calculated from <m>x=$x1 </m>, i.e., equation you just calculated above.  That's why we denote it <m>L_{ $x1  }</m>.)</p>

